a, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Umfreville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Umfreville (La Manche) or Offranville (Seine-Maritime)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Thomas de Umfreville Of Rddesdale was born in 1361, in Castle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Agnes D'Umfravale. He died in 1391, in his hometown, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1361–1391":"1361–1391","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1491–1535":"1491–1535","1535":"1535","1420":"1420","1365":"1365","1361":"1361","1491":"1491","1391":"1391","Castle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Castle, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1361–1391":"1361–1391","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1491–1535":"1491–1535","1535":"1535","1420":"1420","1365":"1365","1361":"1361","1491":"1491","1391":"1391","Castle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Castle, Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1361–1391":"1361–1391","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1491–1535":"1491–1535","1535":"1535","1420":"1420","1365":"1365","1361":"1361","1491":"1491","1391":"139